Welcome to the 13th iteration of this thread! Ask your simpler game questions here, and see them answered (usually!)

We use a particular format, so please be sure to number your questions and answers accordingly. Also, please attempt to search the forum before you ask; the answer may have been posted in a previous thread.

Format Example:

Person with a questionQ1: If the ship moves, and we don't arrive at a planet, what happens to the planets we scanned?

(Person with an answer) A1: Those planets are lost forever, and you have to scan for new ones.

Before you post, consider this:

You probably shouldn't reveal too many details about your ship in your question. If your character isn't an important part of your question, leave your identity out. Whether you're Mush should also be left out, unless the question directly relates to Mush activity.

If people need more details in order to answer your question, they'll ask for them.

We've seen FAR too many newbies post things like, "I'm so and so and Mush, and this is what's going on on my ship." before asking a question...without realizing that experienced people not only read the forum, they might also read that very question, and might be on your ship. That usually ends badly for the person asking the question.

A13: If you read everything what you get, it would be clear, but not being a rude pal:

Goldmode works only when you're on a ship. If you end one ship and don't start another, you won't lose any more days until you join new ship. If your gold mode ends during a ship, you will keep it until the end of the ship.

After goldmode ends, you're granted silver mode permanently.

Keep it in mind that if someone send you a 6day goldmode as gift, you don't get silver after it expires.

[6826491]

A17: http://mushpedia.com/wiki/Titles

A title only initially transfers upon death or inactivity of the title holder. Unless that event happens upon the cycle change, then the title changes hands at the start of the following cycle. If an inactive player who is higher on the chain of title holding suddenly becomes active, the title transfers back to them at the following cycle change.

[8807528]

Q126 What is the repair/fixing priority? I know O2 tanks are #1 but if there's a fire in dorms wouldn't you extinguish that first? NERON is killing us big time.
On july 17, 2015
Peanutz
Mais pourquoi est-il aussi mÃ©chant ?

It depends on the situation of your ship. Sometimes, if you can afford to lose a little oxygen, you can drop a drone to fix the O2 tanks. A dorm fire would certainly need to be extinguished asap, and people healed if there were other types of physical damage like steel plates and / or roomshakes. A fire in the engine room or bridge should also be extinguished fast, before it damages equipment (or more equipment that it has already broken).

Other times, especially in late ships and if you have Automatic Sprinklers, you can afford to ignore certain fires for one or two cycles.

As for the repair priority, the gravity simulator and O2 tanks are usually the top-most priority. The equipment needed to move the ship (command terminal, combustion chamber, emergency reactor, fuel tank) should be repaired manually if you need to escape hunters, otherwise a drone is enough.

Drones are also enough for most of the other equipment, and some of them don't need to be fixed at all (surgery pod for example, comms terminal and antenna if you are done with comms, lab or Neron's core after research and projects are finished, or fuel tanks if you don't need them immediately).

One of the highest priorities is also healing. When you start to get lovely combinations of fires, steel plates, electrical spikes and roomshakes, then it is essential to heal people before doing anything else.

I've been to Eden twice on randoms now, and generally my ships only focus on O2 before starting the starmap run. It's basically up to the RNG anyway - you can be lucky and arrive on Eden before D10, or drain three Astros' worth of AP for 20 days and not get the planets or expo results you need.

The question is: are the risks of going to Cristalite with live mush really worth that extra roll or two of the dice? Especially when added to the inherent risks of exploring with live mush (which you usually have to live with for at least one O2 run)?

Consider:

* Without a Diplomat, you also risk leaving key crew open for a well-timed rampage if they find combat instead of a starmap. Also true of regular expos, but 18-strength combat only makes this more dangerous.
* Combat damage can be offset by distributing weapons, but can everyone be trusted?
* Spores are not just conversion risks. Besides opening up the mush team's strategic options for conversions, they also provide free transfer bait. Remember those weapons you secured and put only in the hands of confirmed humans for the expo? Well...
* Cristalite also carries a risk of MIA. This is a fairly normal risk of exploring since it's only one of several MIA zones, but can easily set you back one active crewmate anyway.

Or: you can find a starmap and be one step closer to Eden if the mush team is defeated.

A150: 7 for Bronze and Silver players, 8 for Gold. Assuming there are no deaths, and no panic attacks before D2C1:

-2 morale at the day change if Chun is traded away, quarantined, not yet awake, or does not have MoH. (I mention traded away or quarantined, since neither results in morale loss.)

Panic attacks are always -3 morale, and I've had them as early as D2. I can't recall ever seeing one on D1, but I won't rule out the possibility.

If there is at least one trader outside, you can press "Shortwave Radio" button and see his/their offer(s). If you are comm manager, you can accept or decline them, if you are not - then only watch.

There are two totally different screens you can enter from comm terminal.

2) Trader screen - it looks like this http://mushpedia.com/images/thumb/3/3... If there are no traders outside, you will not see a button to enter it.
Check which one you are watching

No
What happens if I Exit now?
Nothing, you can exit/enter these screens with no ap cost as many times as you want.

[6826491]

A220: If you had enough solid evidence to justify killing them, then the judges would take that into account, in case it's reported. You can (and often should) have some sort of discussion with people you trust (confirmed humans or not, but better if they're confirmed.) This does two things. One, it establishes the thought process that leads up to the killing, and two, it shows that it wasn't done randomly.

We in the SDF really despise people just randomly killing others, because it leads to morale loss, and often sanctions, and to the dark places where the Old Ones reside...

Now, some kills are made based on some degree of intuition, and the evidence might not be as solid as you would prefer. I've had to do that on more than a few occasions. If you must do this, explain your reasons afterward, whether you were right or wrong. One of the worst things you can do is kill people, and NOT have any reasoning given SOMEWHERE...this leaves it up to our interpretation, and you don't want us assuming that it was randomly done.

Other times, you have to kill someone not because of suspicion of Mushy behavior, but because they're hogging a title and clearly NOT helping the ship. Say, a Paola who stays in the dorms, and doesn't work on anything but projects...or just logs in enough to steal the title back, but doesn't take any actions.

A221: You're Comms Officer - being able to speak from anywhere without a WT/iTrakie (provided you're not rendered silent by an injury) is inherent to the title.

Q288 If as mush, you have never eaten, how quickly does your old body start to starve after transfer?
On october 1, 2015
Peanutz
Mais pourquoi est-il aussi mÃ©chant ?

It depends on when you transfer. We all start with 0 satisfaction. When it reaches -24, humans get the "starvation" status and start losing hp the following cycle.

The mush have the same satisfaction. If you start on D1C1 and transfer on D3C1, your old body won't starve until D4C1. If you transfer after D4C1, your old body will be starving and will lose hp at the following cycle change.

If you have eaten, then you must count 24 cycles after eating, and add the satisfaction of the food you had. For example, if you ate a ration (4 satisfaction) on D2C1, you will starve (or reach the starvation level if you're mush) on D5C5.

Q 317: How exactly does calculation of Eden coordinates happen?

And thanks for the interesting info, Peanutz!
On october 24, 2015
Kenik

A317 A quote from the wiki:
Getting to Eden
There are multiple steps required to end the game by reaching Eden:
Pilgred Repaired
Star Map Fragment obtained from Expedition
Star Map Fragment researched in the Laboratory to Create the Calculator in the Nexus
Two further Star Map Fragments obtained
All three map fragments must be moved to the Nexus
Access the Calculator (Cannot be Dirty)
Calculating Costs 2 Action Point with a Base success of 33%. When the calculation is complete you will get the message "[Character] worked at it to no avail, there was no way to triangulate the data... Suddenly a violente shudder causes a motherboard to fall on their head and their eyes light up. Eureka! You have to think outside the box! [Character] then proceeds to discover the coordinates of the Edenists."
Once the Coordinates have been calculated, the Command will have the option on their command console to take the ship to Eden, this is a one-click action that will end the game immediately.

Well then, A 317 b :
The calculation happens at the Super Calculator at Nexus. The Super Calculator's progress is strictly individual. Therefore, no relays are needed (or helpful). The percentage on the button is not a progress of calculation but a chance. If the calculation fails, the percentage improves.

It is unknown to what amount it improves and it is unknown if there's some hidden bonus for the certain skills. At my ship, the improvement was 8% and then success. It is unknown if someone else's participation ruins the progress.
